Introduction

Obesity is a major public health concern in Scotland and is regularly monitored through the Scottish Health Survey. Examining changes in obesity prevalence over time can help identify trends, and understand whether the situation is improving, worsening, or staying the same. This analysis explores whether the prevalence of obesity in Scotland changed between 2013 and 2016. The proportions for each year are compared using the relative percentages of the "Yes" factor (individuals classified as obese) and the "No" factor (individuals not classified as obese) to determine whether there were any noticeable changes in prevalence across the given years.

Question of Interest:

Has the prevalence of obesity in Scotland changed over the given years of the Scottish Health Survey?

Question of Interest: Are there any differences in obesity by age, gender, socio-economic status or lifestyle factors?

This section explores obesity prevalence using data from the Scottish Health Survey (2013–2016). The response variable is obesity status (Yes/No). Differences in obesity prevalence are examined across age group, sex, employment status, and lifestyle factors such as fruit and vegetable intake. Approximately 30% of individuals in the dataset are classified as obese. The plots below compare obesity prevalence across these groups.

Exploratory Analysis

{r}
#| message: false
#| warning: false
#| echo: false

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(broom)
library(yardstick)  

health<- read.csv("DAProject3.csv")

{r}
#| echo: false

health.obesity<- health %>%
  select(Obese, Year)

{r}
#| echo: false
#| message: false
#| warning: false
library(janitor)
health.obesity %>%
  tabyl(Year, Obese) %>%
  adorn_percentages() %>%
  adorn_pct_formatting() %>%
  adorn_ns() # To show original counts

This output above shows the percentage data in an organised way.

{r}
#| echo: false
#| label: barplot1
ggplot(health.obesity, aes(x = Year, group = Obese)) +
    geom_bar(aes(y = after_stat(prop), fill = Obese), 
             stat = "count", position = "dodge") +
    labs(y = "Proportion", fill = "Obese", title = "Barplot of Obesity for the Years(2013-2016)")


From the barplot, we can see that:

In 2013, the proportion of individuals classified as obese was higher for the "Yes" factor, accounting for 69.7%, compared with the "No" factor at 30.3%.

Similarly, in 2014 the "Yes" factor continued to represent the larger proportion of obesity at 69.8%, while the "No" factor accounted for 30.2%.

A similar pattern is observed in the following years. In 2015, the "Yes" factor represented 69.4% of the proportion, compared with 30.6% for the "No" factor.

In 2016, the "Yes" factor again had the higher proportion at 69.5%, while the "No" factor accounted for 30.5%.

